n 'bg-primary' as one of the classes.\n\nBut wait - is it a `div` or another element? Let me check...\n\nThe test infrastructure shows the ggp has class with bg-primary. Let me check the actual tag.\n\nActually I should also check if there might be timing issues - the element might not be loaded when the test checks.\n\nLet me check if there's a problem with the `scrollIntoViewIfNeeded` call BEFORE `waitFor`. If `scrollIntoViewIfNeeded` throws an error (element not in DOM yet), it's caught with `.catch(() => undefined)`. But then `waitFor` is called and if the element isn't in DOM yet, it times out.\n\nThe real fix should be:\n1. Wait for `networkidle` properly before attempting to find the newsletter section\n2. Use a more resilient scroll strategy\n3. Use `page.locator(...).waitFor({ state: 'attached', timeout: ... })` first to confirm DOM presence, then scroll, then wait for visible\n\nActually, the most likely root cause: the newsletter section is loaded by Builder.io dynamically. In the test environment on CI, Builder.io might be blocked or slow, causing the section to never load.\n\n**Fix for TC-83232**: \n1. Use `input[placeholder=\"Enter your email\"]` as the primary selector (more stable, not dependent on class structure)\n2. Or alternatively, try `footer input[type=\"email\"]` as fallback - but the comment says it's NOT in footer\n3. Actually: use `[class*=\"bg-primary\"] input[type=\"email\"]` which is more flexible than `div.bg-primary`\n\nBut actually, the problem might be at the DOM vs. visibility level. Let me check if `div.bg-primary` selector works.\n\nActually I suspect the real issue is: sometimes the newsletter section doesn't load at all (Builder.io failure), causing infinite timeout. The fix is:\n1. Broader selector with `[class*=bg-primary]` instead of `div.bg-primary`\n2. Better wait strategy: use `waitFor({ state: 'attached' })` first with longer timeout, then scroll, then wait for visible\n3. Skip the test gracefully if the section doesn't load (mark as pending/skipped)\n\nThe simplest and most effective fix:\n- Change selector in HomePage.ts to use `[class*=\"bg-primary\"] input[type=\"email\"]` and also add a fallback via `input[placeholder=\"Enter your email\"]`\n- In the test, use `waitFor({ state: 'attached' })` before scrolling to confirm the element is in DOM\n\nActually, looking at the selector: `div.bg-primary input[type=\"email\"]`. In CSS, `div.bg-primary` means a `div` element with class `bg-primary`. But in Tailwind, `bg-primary` is one class among many. The element has class `mx-auto mt-10 bg-primary px-4 ...`. So `div.bg-primary` DOES match it (bg-primary is in the class list).\n\nLet me check if this is maybe an issue with the `div` part - what if the element is a `section` instead of a `div`?\n\nLet me check this in the browser.\n"}}
