{"event": "tool_call", "tool": "think", "args": {"thought": "The structure is confirmed:\n- INPUT (class: w-full rounded-none p-3 text-black outline-none)\n  - DIV (class: lg:col-span-1)\n    - DIV (class: mx-auto grid max-w-[1272px] grid-cols-3 items-center gap-4 s...)\n      - DIV (class: mx-auto mt-10 bg-primary px-4 pb-5 pt-3 text-center leading-...)\n        - BODY\n          - HTML\n\nSo the structure is: BODY > DIV.bg-primary > DIV > DIV > INPUT\n\nThe selector `div.bg-primary input[type=\"email\"]` SHOULD match this! The great-grandparent is a `div` with class including `bg-primary`.\n\nBut wait - the element is a DIRECT child of BODY! So the newsletter section is at `body > div.bg-primary`. This means the selector SHOULD work.\n\nThe issue must be timing - the newsletter section loads async via Builder.io. When the test runs, the div doesn't exist in DOM yet. The test needs to WAIT for the section to appear in DOM before trying to interact with it.\n\nCurrent test approach:\n1. Scroll to bottom\n2. Wait for networkidle (10s, soft fail)\n3. Wait 500ms\n4. scrollIntoViewIfNeeded (5s, soft fail)\n5. Poll 8 times with 800ms between (6.4s total)\n6. waitFor visible 30s\n\nBut the problem is: if the element is NOT in the DOM during the scroll (because Builder.io hasn't loaded it yet), `scrollIntoViewIfNeeded` will fail silently (caught), and the poll loop will also fail (isVisible returns false). Then `waitFor` with 30s timeout starts. By this point, we've already wasted ~17-18s on the scroll + poll, leaving only 12-13s for the actual wait.\n\nBut the comment says the element was confirmed in DOM inspection. And my browser test shows it IS there after waiting. So the issue is the element might mount AFTER a delay that's longer than 30s total.\n\nActually, the element in my browser inspection shows it's at `body > div.bg-primary > ...`. It IS in the DOM. But the Playwright `waitFor({ state: 'visible' })` - could there be an issue with visibility?\n\nThe rect shows `top: -174` - the element is ABOVE the viewport after scrolling to bottom. But `visible` in Playwright means \"has non-zero bounding box\" not \"is in viewport\". The bounding box is 352x43 so it IS visible.\n\nWait - could the issue be that `div.bg-primary` matches MULTIPLE elements and the FIRST one is not the newsletter input? Let me check how many `div.bg-primary` elements exist.\n\nFrom my earlier check: `bgPrimary=8` - there are 8 elements with bg-primary in class. The locator `div.bg-primary input[type=\"email\"]` uses the FIRST one. But `.first()` is on the outer locator, meaning it returns the first INPUT[type=email] found inside ANY div.bg-primary. Since there's only 1 input[type=email], this should be fine.\n\nHmm. Let me try the Playwright locator directly to see if it can find the element.\n\nActually, the test log says:\n```\nCall log:\n  - waiting for locator('div.bg-primary input[type=\"email\"]').first() to be visible\n```\n\nAnd the timeout was 30s. The element IS in DOM when I check. But maybe on the CI run, the element isn't there or is hidden.\n\nLet me also verify: the current scroll is at the BOTTOM (scrollTo(scrollHeight)). The newsletter is at top=-174 relative to viewport, meaning it's ABOVE the current scroll position. The body height is 4535px and the viewport is 720px. If scrolled to bottom, the newsletter might be at pixel ~3000-4000 from top.\n\nActually the scroll position issue: after `window.scrollTo(0, document.body.scrollHeight)` the scroll position is at the very bottom (4535 - 720 = 3815 from top). The element at top=-174 means it's at about 3815 - 174 = 3641px from the top of the page, which is WITHIN the scrolled range.\n\nBut Playwright's `waitFor({ state: 'visible' })` doesn't check viewport intersection - it just checks if the element has non-zero dimensions and is not hidden by CSS. So this should pass.\n\nOK, I'm confused about why it's failing. Let me try a different approach:\n\nThe most likely real cause: **On CI/chromium/edge, the Builder.io section NEVER LOADS** because the request is blocked, slow, or returns an error. The 8 elements with bg-primary include some that are always rendered (like the header, buttons), but the NEWSLETTER SECTION specifically might not render if the Builder.io fetch fails.\n\nSo the element is NOT in the DOM when the test runs (maybe on certain environments it just doesn't load).\n\nIn that case, the fix should be:\n1. Try to wait for the element longer\n2. Have a fallback that skips/warns if newsletter section doesn't load\n3. OR find a way to trigger the newsletter section without relying on Builder.io\n\nActually, looking at the 8 bgPrimary elements in the current page - the newsletter IS one of them. But in a fresh CI load, maybe it doesn't appear.\n\n**The real fix for TC-83232:**\n1. Before scrolling, wait for `networkidle` with a LONGER timeout (30s instead of 10s)\n2. After scroll to bottom, wait for the specific element to appear in DOM with `waitFor({ state: 'attached' })` first\n3. Then trigger scrollIntoView to make it visible\n\nLet me also check if there's an issue with `waitFor({ state: 'visible' })` vs. just `waitFor({ state: 'attached' })`. Maybe the element IS in DOM but not \"visible\" by Playwright's definition (e.g., inside a hidden parent).\n\nActually, looking at the test code again at line 409-440:\n- Line 440: `await homePage.newsletterEmailInput.waitFor({ state: 'visible', timeout: 30_000 });`\n\nThis is the 30s that times out. But the test has ALREADY spent time scrolling (8 retries × 800ms = 6.4s + initial scroll + 500ms wait + scrollIntoViewIfNeeded). So by line 440, the 30s timeout means we get about 37s total (from step start). \n\nBut actually the `timeout: 30_000` in the `waitFor` call is an ABSOLUTE timeout of 30s from when that call starts, not from test start. And the test GLOBAL timeout is 60s. So if the scroll steps take 15-20s, and then 30s more, we'd exceed the 60s global timeout... but the error says the 30s